However my  answer to the question of recommending this course is low because of the covid situation in our world.  My answer is not because of the integrity of the course, the suggestions or the "gist" of the course. The instructors were excellent.  The philosophy of equity and responsibility is also. But I cannot recommend this course in light of covid-19. I feel teaching EL through distance learning with integrity would not be possible.
what_could_have_improved_your_experience: There was difficulty with navigating between guides and other materials for me. I feel that the open source guides would be much easier to use if, when a direction is made, the page and book where the material is found was included.
why_did_you_choose_this_rating: I chose this rating because I do not feel that EL can be taught correctly with distance learning. There is almost no support for using these materials that way. If a school pays this much money for this program, every part should be easily accessed by a student at home, and teachers should not have to put it into google or another program themselves. We should be the facilitators, not creating online resources.

learning_to_try_out: I'm not sure that I learned anything. This is my 3rd or 4th workshop on the shifts. The guidebooks came out years ago, and I've unfortunately used them since then. Today was extremely repetitive. I would be shocked if anyone in this room didn't already know about the shifts, or if anyone taught in the "before shifts" way.
overall_what_went_well_in_this_professio: It was nice to see the other teachers. In between tasks, we were able to talk about what we're teaching and share ideas. It was helpful.
what_could_have_improved_your_experience:
I'm unhappy I had to come today. It's the second week of school, so holding this at a later date would be a big improvement. 
 I also find it hard to believe that anyone in this room know all of this content already. If there is anyone who didn't know, they should have their own PD and let the rest of us move on. 
 We spent an hour learning about why PDs are good. Why? Couldn't that hour have been better spent? 
 All morning felt like guidebook propaganda. It felt like we were being persuaded to love them. It doesn't matter if we like them or not (and most of us don't), we still have to teach them. 
 Today would be much better if we actually learned something relevant instead of things we all know and an infomercial for the guidebooks.
